reviewText:
I purchased this game at full price the week before promotion. And in the following week, I played for nearly 60 hrs. This is a really fantastic game, it is turn-based, and lots of interaction with the environment. You can probably kill boss in numerous creative ways! Quests are interesting and lots of modern humors inside.

Pros:
Strategic Caculation;
Dynamic Environment;
Funny Dialogue;
Full voice;
Interaction with animals!

Cons:
It's slow, very slow;
Performs badly on Macbook;
Heavy on texts, so better to be patient;

Overall:
Recommend!

Divinity: Original Sin started as a kickstarter campaign to become one of the best CRPGs I have ever seen, new and old. If you miss the old times playing Baldur's Gate, Shining Force, and the like, you will love this game. If you don't know what those are, but are a fan of RPGs in general, you will love this game. If you ever wondered what D&D would look like if it was created for PC in 2014, you will love this game. In short, you will love this game.

Pros:

Combat is extremely fun, the AI is (comparatively) smart, and there's no shortage of enemies of all kinds. As expected, the battlefield plays a big role in combat as well, and either side is able to mold it to their advantage;
The story is great, if a bit cliché. But it's nonetheless well written and will make you overlook the boring aspects. There is also a good amount of humor in the game (the good kind, not the meme kind);
Incredible depth in character growth and customization. You can be anything you want. Choices are also part of your character growth, depending on your dialogue choices, or how you decide to finish a quest. Expect to spend a lot of time deciding which build you want to go with. Such is life, and you will love it.
The out of combat puzzles are a challenge of their own. It takes more than brute force to get through the game, and that's a wonderful thing. This game truly makes you think outside of the box sometimes;
Because of the way the game is laid out to you, every step you successfully advance feels rewarding. There was no dull part in the story, at least for me. Side quests and exploration provide an extra layer of rewarding feelings;
You can do LITERALLY ANYTHING you want. NPC looked at you funny? Burn him down. Boss is boring you with its monologue? Switch characters and smite him right in the face. Vendor has an item you want but you can't afford it? Pickpocket him. Or just kill him too. Who cares. You're the boss. You go you;
Online and local co-op support. Because sometimes doing everything your way alone is boring. It's also extremely fun to co-op if you're a roleplay person. The game was developed with co-op in mind and that's the right way to play it.
Cons:

Due to the length and nature of this game, playing co-op if you don't have a friend to compromise and play with you, or can't find a partner for that only purpose, is nigh impossible. The in-game lobby was empty every time I looked. And, at the time of this review, it's a less than 5 months old game;
The beginning of the game is extremely tiring. You are sent by some people to some town to do something, defeat a couple of enemies on the way, and your next 5 hours or so are spent walking around the town talking to people. It will catch up after that, but a lot of people give up before it happens;
The characters in this game are obnoxious. Every. Single. One. Of. Them. NPCs will repeat the same phrase every two seconds if you're near them. N/PCs have awful personalities. I guess it's somewhat justified since they've lived awful lives, as you come to find out, but for me, as a player, I've left PCs out of my main party because they were so annoying; Quiet day on the market my bum.
Combat in this game actually gets easier the more your progress. This is due the fact you have access to highly overpowered skills later on, and I'm talking wiping the whole enemy party in one shot" kind of OP. There is a point where defeating enemies stops being a challenge and becomes a chore.
Not exactly a con
